{
  "answer": "**In the *Manusmṛti*, the first action of the day for a *snātaka* (Brahmin graduate or householder) is to awaken during the *Brahma-muhūrta* (the final pre-dawn watch of the night, roughly 96 minutes before sunrise) and contemplate *dharma*, *artha*, and the body's ills.**[^1] He then performs ablutions and stands for the dawn twilight worship (*uṣas-saṃdhyā*).\n\n**In the *Yājñavalkya Smṛti*, the first action is likewise rising (*utthāya*) at the *Brāhma-muhūrta* to reflect upon one's own welfare (*ātmakalyāṇa*):**[^2] ablutions and teeth-cleaning follow, leading into the dawn twilight rites.\n\nThe texts agree on rising early at the *Brahma-muhūrta* as the initial step—only the phrasing of the accompanying reflection differs slightly (*dharma* and *artha* in Manu; general welfare in Yājñavalkya). Both proceed to purification and twilight worship without variation in sequence. No disagreement exists.[^3]\n\n[^1]: *Manusmṛti*, Chapter 4, [paragraph](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/04/translation/#p-e69207).\n\n[^2]: *Yājñavalkya Smṛti*, Chapter 1, [paragraph](/works/unknown-yajnavalkya-smrti-cb88d6/01/translation/#p-47d074).\n\n[^3]: *Manusmṛti*, Chapter 4, [paragraph](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/04/translation/#p-4ea946); *Yājñavalkya Smṛti*, Chapter 1, [paragraph](/works/unknown-yajnavalkya-smrti-cb88d6/01/translation/#p-596a25).",
